<span id="freeTextContainer16667627294519932790">Need to think about this one a bit before I review it as my minds a little blown and all over the place. In a very good way. Alderman creates an empowering (pun not intended) and in turns terrifying* alternate world where power is literally (and electrifyingly) in women&apos;s hands and follows how the power effects them. Which is the greater power; love, hate, survival, revenge?<br/><br/>*Not terrifying because women are in charge but because of what some of them do with their power. As terrifying as men, whi</span>
  <span id="freeText16667627294519932790" style="display:none">Need to think about this one a bit before I review it as my minds a little blown and all over the place. In a very good way. Alderman creates an empowering (pun not intended) and in turns terrifying* alternate world where power is literally (and electrifyingly) in women's hands and follows how the power effects them. Which is the greater power; love, hate, survival, revenge?<br /><br />*Not terrifying because women are in charge but because of what some of them do with their power. As terrifying as men, which is the point I know and it's very well done. </span>
